# matrics visualization


# Histograms

# TIME

# Compute mean and standard deviation of your data
mean_time <- mean(matrics$Time)
sd_time <- sd(matrics$Time)

# Create a ggplot object
ggplot(matrics, aes(x = Time)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.5, fill = "lightblue", color = "blue", aes(y = ..density..)) + # Histogram of your data
  stat_function(fun = dnorm, args = list(mean = mean_time, sd = sd_time), color = "red", size = 1) + # Overlay normal distribution curve
  labs(title = "Histogram of Time Metric with Overlayed Normal Distribution Curve",
       x = "Total Time spent in Supermarket", y = "Density") +
  theme_minimal()

# Table of basic metrics

# Gather the data into long format
data_long <- matrics %>%
  gather(variable, value)

# Calculate statistics for each variable
summary_table <- data_long %>%
  group_by(variable) %>%
  summarize(
    mean = mean(value),
    median = median(value),
    Q1 = quantile(value, probs = 0.25),
    Q2 = quantile(value, probs = 0.5),
    Q3 = quantile(value, probs = 0.75)
  )

# Print the summary table
print(summary_table)

# Correlation matrix


# Method 1
correlation_matrix <- cor(matrics)

# Plot heatmap of correlation matrix
heatmap(correlation_matrix, 
        col = colorRampPalette(c("blue", "white", "red"))(100), 
        scale = "none", 
        symm = TRUE, 
        margins = c(10, 10))

# Method 2
correlation_matrix <- cor(matrics)

# Convert correlation matrix to a data frame
correlation_df <- as.data.frame(as.table(correlation_matrix))
names(correlation_df) <- c("Var1", "Var2", "Correlation")

# Plot heatmap of correlation matrix
ggplot(data = correlation_df, aes(x = Var1, y = Var2, fill = Correlation)) +
  geom_tile() +
  scale_fill_gradient(low = "blue", high = "red", limits = c(0.6, 1)) +
  labs(title = "Correlation Heatmap",
       x = "Variable",
       y = "Variable") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

# Other relationships within variables


# Pairwise scatterplot matrix
pairs(matrics)

# Normalized density curves

# Function to normalize density
normalize_density <- function(dens) {
  dens$y <- dens$y / sum(dens$y) # Normalize y-values
  dens
}

# Loop through each variable in your dataset
for (col in names(matrics)) {
  # Estimate density for each variable
  density_data <- density(matrics[[col]])
  
  # Normalize density
  normalized_density <- normalize_density(density_data)
  
  # Plot normalized density curve
  plot(normalized_density, main = paste("Normalized Density Curve of", col), 
       xlab = "Value", ylab = "Density")
}
